prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: cores in CO-cloud FOG, part 1
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: Observe 53 of the 94 clumps in FOG cloud in Band6 to look for cores: continuum and C18O, 13CO(2-1)

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: The sensitivity criterion is based on the continuum observations, thus the representative window was chosen accordingly and bears no relation to the line observations.

The resolution of 1.5 arcsec corresponds to 0.07pc at the distance of the target (9.3kpc), comparable to the typical size of molecular cores, while the maximum recoverable scale (10" = 0.45pc) is adequate as we are not interested in the more extended inter-core emission component.

Continuum: From our Herschel 250 micron background-subtracted map (hpbw 18 arcsec) we identified 94 clumps with masses 2-920 Msun (assuming gas temperature T=15K, which is derived from our SEST 12CO(1-0) map of this region).[We used the image at 250 micron because it offers the best compromise between resolution and data quality in terms of low noise levels.] Within these clumps are the molecular cores and we want to be able to detect those that can form stars. We thus aim for a minimum mass of the order of the Jeans mass, which is about 1Msun (at T=15K and vol. dens. 10^(4-5) per cc). At 1.3mm 1Msun corresponds to an integrated flux of 0.37mJy. For this to be a 3-4sigma detection the required sensitivity is 0.1mJy per pointing over a total bandwidth of 5.63GHz (3x1.875GHz).
Lines: Based on our unpublished C18O(2-1) observations in the northern part of the main cloud (JCMT, 20" beam, on 10" grid) we expect to find typical line temps. (Tmb) of about 0.5-1K at positions away from the IRAS sources. The emission shows structure from one grid point to the next and also in the Herschel map at 160 micron we see unresolved compact structures of the order of the beam size (11".5). We conservatively assume the C18O emission to be uniformly distributed over a region of the order of the max. recoverable size (ca. 10"). Then the typical JCMT line temps. would correspond to ca. 180-360mJy at the 1.5 arcsec ALMA resolution. For this to be a 10sigma detection requires a 18-36mJy sensitivity. In both cases the integration time needed to reach this sensitivity in a 0.25 km/s channel (the linewidths are ca. 1.5 km/s) is less than the on-source time necessary to reach the required continuum sensitivity, which is the criterion used for this proposal. 13CO(2-1) is always much stronger than C18O(2-1) [by a factor of 7-8 in our JCMT observations] and more or less distributed in the same way.
NB: The project is split into two SG only because with all 94 targets in one SG the length of the source list left no room for the spectral setup table, which was off the bottom of the page in the pdf file! Unfortunately this has increased the total time by almost 1 hour. There is no technical reason why all 94 targets could not be in a single SG.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: The distribution over mass of stars at birth, the initial mass function (IMF) is one of the most important parameters in star-formation research. It is still not clear what determines the IMF, nor whether the IMF is the same for every star forming region. It does seem, however, that the IMF is set very early on by the masses of the molecular cores out of which the stars form. The core mass function (CMF), and by consequence the IMF, may however depend on the physical and chemical properties of the environment. So far, CMFs (and, with few exceptions, IMFs) have been determined in molecular clouds (and star clusters) in the solar neighbourhood and the inner Galaxy. We propose to determine the CMF in a molecular cloud in the far-outer reaches of our Galaxy (galactocentric distance 16 kpc), where conditions are very different from the inner Galaxy. We do this by continuum and line observations of 94 clumps identified from Herschel 250 micron images of this cloud; each clump is assumed to contain one or more cores, of sizes comparable to the ALMA beam. We aim to be able to detect cores with masses of the order of the Jeans mass (1 Msun).
